Here is something fun you might notice: #strong[ůĪ§č esun] generally means 'to
swap', but there's enough information in the sentences to know that it
specifically means 'to sell' in one sentence, and 'to buy' in another!

== more about mute

#strong[ůĪ§ľ mute] is a very useful word to have. We don't see adjectives attach to
pronouns #strong[ůĪ§ī mi], #strong[ůĪ•ě sina], #strong[ůĪ•Ü ona] all that often, but
#strong[ůĪ§ľ mute] is so useful that it does that quite frequently:

#list((
  word("ůĪ§īůĪ§ľ", "mi mute", "we, many of us"),
  sentence(
    "ůĪ§üůĪ•ČůĪ§ßůĪ§ďůĪ§ČůĪ§īůĪ§ľ",
    "kulupu pali li jo e mi mute.",
    "The labour union includes a lot of us.",
  ),
  word("ůĪ•ěůĪ§ľ", "sina mute", "you lot, you guys, y'all"),
  sentence(
    "ůĪ•ÜůĪ§ßůĪ§ėůĪ•†ůĪ§ČůĪ•ěůĪ§ľ",
    "ona li ken sitelen e sina mute.",
    "They can take a picture of you guys.",
  ),
))

Remember the special rule that says: "when #strong[ůĪ§ī mi] or #strong[ůĪ•ě sina] is
the subject of the sentence, we remove the #strong[ůĪ§ß li]"? That rule is quite
specific! Take a look at these sentences:

#list((
  sentence("ůĪ§īůĪ§ľůĪ§ßůĪ§ēůĪ§Ľ", "mi mute li kalama musi.", "We perform music together."),
  sentence("ůĪ•ěůĪ§ľůĪ§ßůĪ•°ůĪ§ČůĪ•Ā", "sina mute li sona e ni.", "Many of you know this."),
))

Notice how the #strong[ůĪ§ß li] isn't dropped. This is because the subject isn't
either #strong[ůĪ§ī mi] or #strong[ůĪ•ě sina], but instead #strong[ůĪ§īůĪ§ľ mi mute] and
#strong[ůĪ•ěůĪ§ľ sina mute]!

It might seem like an odd quirk, but remember --- the purpose of #strong[ůĪ§ß li]
is to show where the verb starts! If it was dropped here, we would instead
assume #strong[ůĪ§ľ mute] is the verb.
